### Summary of the problem

The target program contains a double free, which is detected by libc. During the processing of the code libc invokes to terminate the process on such an event manticore raises an IOError that looks as follows (the full log is linked below):

```
2017-10-27 15:33:28,749: [30775] m.c.executor:ERROR: Exception: [Errno 29] Illegal seek
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/core/executor.py", line 472, in run
    self.fork(current_state, e.expression, e.policy, e.setstate)
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/core/executor.py", line 405, in fork
    state_id = self.enqueue(new_state)
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/core/executor.py", line 258, in enqueue
    state_id = self._workspace.save_state(state)
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/core/workspace.py", line 393, in save_state
    self._store.save_state(state, '{}{:08x}{}'.format(self._prefix, id_, self._suffix))
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/core/workspace.py", line 153, in save_state
    self._serializer.serialize(state, f)
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/core/workspace.py", line 43, in serialize
    f.write(cPickle.dumps(state, 2))
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/platforms/linux.py", line 52, in __getstate__
    state['pos'] = self.tell()
  File "/home/user/git/manticore/manticore/platforms/linux.py", line 78, in tell
    return self.file.tell(*args)
IOError: [Errno 29] Illegal seek
```

### Step to reproduce the behavior
Compile the following via `gcc -static -o test_double_free test_double_free.c` and run with `manticore -v --procs=5 test_double_free +`

```
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

void safe(void)
{
    char *p = malloc(100);
    char *v = malloc(200);

    printf("%p %p\n", p, v);

    free(v);
    free(p);
}

void unsafe(void)
{
    char *p = malloc(100);
    char *v = malloc(200);

    printf("%p %p\n", p, v);

    free(v);
    free(p);
    // Bug
    free(p);
}

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    if (argc != 2) {
        printf("Usage: %s X\n", argv[0]);
        printf("\t\tX: 1 for safe, 2 for unsafe\n");
        return 1;
    }

    if (!strcmp(argv[1], "1")) {
        safe();
    } else if (!strcmp(argv[1], "2")) {
        unsafe();
    } else {
        printf("Invalid command\n");
        return 1;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

### Actual behavior

After a minute or so an IOError exception is raised. The full log can be found here https://pastebin.com/936W3Frv

As a `client_credentials` based access token has no refresh token, the `refresh_token()` functionality raises an exception (ie. `InvalidRequestError: Missing refresh token parameter.`). Based on the spec, I believe this is *technically* fine - one should fetch a new access token in this case.

Is it just the spec that prevents `requests-oauthlib` from handling this scenario gracefully alongside the current token expiration code handling in the `request()` method on `OAuth2Session`?

If I subclass `OAuth2Session` like so:

```
class RefreshOAuth2Session(OAuth2Session):
    def request(self, *args, **kwargs):
        try:
            return super().request(*args, **kwargs)
        except TokenExpiredError:
            self.token = self.fetch_token(
                token_url=OAUTH2_TOKEN_URL,
                **self.auto_refresh_kwargs
            )
            self.token_updater(self.token)
            return super().request(*args, **kwargs)
```

I can use it like this:

```
class MyClass(object):
    _session = None
    _token = None

    def token_updater(self, token):
        self._token = token

    @property
    def session(self):
        if self._session is None:
            self._session = RefreshOAuth2Session(
                client=BackendApplicationClient(client_id=self.client_id),
                token=self.token,
                token_updater=self.token_updater,
                auto_refresh_kwargs={
                    'client_id': self.client_id,
                    'client_secret': self.client_secret,
                }
            )
        return self._session

    @property
    def token(self):
        if self._token is None:
            self._token = RefreshOAuth2Session(
                client=BackendApplicationClient(client_id=self.client_id)
            ).fetch_token(
                token_url=OAUTH2_TOKEN_URL,
                client_id=self.client_id,
                client_secret=self.client_secret
            )
        return self._token

    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
        super(MyClass, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)
        self.client_id = CLIENT_ID
        self.client_secret = CLIENT_SECRET

    def get_information(self):
        return self.session.get('https://localhost:10000/api/infomation/')


obj = MyClass()
obj.get_information()
```

As long as `auto_refresh_url` is not passed in, the logic in my subclass handles everything smoothly.  Could logic be added to `request()` to cover this scenario, rather than having to kludge this as I've done?

