When integrating pybind11 with other Python wrapper tools it is often necessary to extract smart pointers from pybind11 wrapped objects or conversely construct a `pybind11::object` from a smart pointer. For instance the following swig typemaps will allow swig wrapped functions to accept and return pybind11 wrapped `MyType` objects (backed by a `shared_ptr`).

    %typemap(out) std::shared_ptr<MyType> {
        /* Use a pybind11 typecaster to create a PyObject from a shared_ptr<MyType> */
        pybind11::detail::type_caster<std::shared_ptr<MyType>> caster;
        pybind11::handle out = caster.cast($1, pybind11::return_value_policy::take_ownership, pybind11::handle());
        $result = out.ptr();
    }

    %typemap(in) std::shared_ptr<MyType> {
        /* First make a pybind11 object handler around the PyObject *
         * Then, cast it to a shared_ptr<MyType> using the pybind11 caster. */
        pybind11::object p{$input, true};
        try {
            std::shared_ptr<MyType> ptr(p.cast<std::shared_ptr<MyType>>());
            $1 = ptr;
        } catch(...) {
            PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, "could not cast to shared_ptr<MyType>");
            return nullptr;
        }
    }

But this exposes quite a bit of the internals of pybind11 (namely the typecaster). It would be nice if pybind11 included a few convenience functions to do this.

